posts.name: Mihai Nicoara
posts.cooked:
We got a new SnakeEyes Red Board today, we hooked it all up according to their documentation (see the pictures for details). Its attached to a Raspberry Pi 3b powered by usb from out roborio. Its flashed with the Snake Eyes firmware according to the settings tab (see image), and we’ve got the led slider to 100, but the lights arent on. Notably, all 4 flash red when the pi is restarted. If this is because the cpu is on low, power, how does one get more power out of a rio? Does anyone know why this problem is happening and how to fix it. Thank you in advance. snaeke1 1918×970 74.1 KB

posts.name: James
posts.cooked:
I’m attempting to solve this same problem.  The main undervoltage problem is caused because even if you are plugging the USB cord into a 5V port (which all USB products are, by design), if the current output is too small (it is) then the voltage will drop.

For more detail, most Wall-to-USB converters output at 500mA because that is the official USB protocol. The only reason it’d be higher is for charging devices. If plugged into the roboRIO, the ports (on the v1 or v2, it doesn’t matter) output 5V at 900mA peak. The Raspberry Pi 1-3 all request 5.1V at 2.5A. 2.5A exceeds the output of the USB ports on the roboRIO, the fuse that any VRMs are connected to on the PDP, and thus requires a custom voltage regulator circuit (either hand made or ordered off of Amazon) that steps down 12+ Volts to 5 Volts at at least 2.5 Amps (I found one that handles 12-60 Volt input and outputs 5-5.2V at 3 Amps, which is fine since it will only draw as much current as it needs).

posts.name: Kim
posts.cooked:
That warning is from the Raspberry Pi, caused when powering the device off of a peripheral that isn’t supplying enough current for it to run normally.  In the current setup depicted, you’re using USB rather than the input pins to the SnakeEyes HAT as their datasheet / website suggests.  The schematic suggests the LEDs are also powered off of those input pins on the HAT

Plug the device into a PDP/PDH port with what the product spec suggests (while complying with CUSTOM CIRCUIT rules) and it’s likely to both make that warning go away, and for the LEDs to work.

Best of luck!

posts.name: James
posts.cooked: It might not be the voltage (the error log shows the last or current error cause). If it is though, you will need to look into getting a DC-to-DC converter that steps down 12V to a stable 5V or so at 2.5 Amps. We tried having the Pi hooked up to two VRMs on the 5V 2A rails (no hat, we don’t use it) and it still would brownout from current draw ant turn off repeatedly. Our electrical mentor is going to make a Buck converter for this, so we can plug it into the PDP.

According to the snake eyes literature, the LEDs will function down to 7V. ( https://www.playingwithfusion.com/include/getfile.php?fileid=7110 ) If you are only powering it through the Rpi’s 5v usb, then the LEDs won’t work. You need to use the snake eyes board’s onboard power supply to power the LEDs, because the LED drivers require far more power than could be provided through the RPi.

For bench testing, I use a 14V 3A supply via a passive POE adapter. I’m using a 12v fan in the case and it is fine at 14 V, it just runs a little faster and louder, but the extra cooling is worth it. Plus, the onboard buck regulator provides (per the specs, I haven’t actually put a meter on mine) 5.1V for the Rpi, which it likes.

Edited to add: If you don’t want to use POE, there is a Weidmuller connector on the snake eyes board to power it that way. Also, @gerthworm has recently added some updated cases and has been updating the snakes-eyes-specific photovision RPi image file. Thanks Chris!
The regulator on the snake eyes board will step down the voltage from 7-36V to 5V. https://www.playingwithfusion.com/include/getfile.php?fileid=7110

Use the power supply on the snakes eyes board to power the RPi, rather than buying a separate one.  That is why it is there. The specs say it will provide 5.05V at 2.5A. Playing With Fusion - SnakeEyes (Green) Visible Raspberry Pi HAT for FRC Robotic Vision

posts.name: Chris Gerth
posts.cooked:
All the wiring advice here is correct, you’ll want to power the whole thing either through POE on the ethernet input, or through the weldimulers. 12-18v in all cases.

Additionally, in photonvision, be sure to run a retroreflective pipeline. LED’s won’t be enabled for any other pipeline.
